# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afrojack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] The **53rd Annual Grammy Awards** were held on February 13, 2011, at the Staples Center in Los Angeles.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] They were broadcast on CBS with a rating of 26.6 million viewers.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] Barbra Streisand was honored as the MusiCares Person of the Year two nights prior to the telecast on February 11.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] Nominations were announced on December 1, 2010 and a total of 108 awards were presented.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] Most of the awards were presented during the pre-telecast, which took place at the Los Angeles Convention Center next to the Staples Center, where the main telecast took place.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] The eligibility period was October 1, 2009 to September 30, 2010.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] For the third year, nominations were announced on prime-time television as part of "The GRAMMY Nominations Concert Live! – Countdown to Music's Biggest Night" a one-hour special broadcast live on CBS from Club Nokia at L.A.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] Arcade Fire won Album of the Year for *The Suburbs* becoming the first indie act to do so, and surprising many viewers and critics.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] Baba Yetu composed and arranged by Christopher Tin won Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s), the first Grammy given to a piece of music written for a video game.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] Esperanza Spalding was awarded Best New Artist.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] Lady Antebellum won five awards including Record of the Year and Song of the Year for "Need You Now".
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] Other multiple winners include: David Frost, John Legend, Lady Gaga, Jay-Z, and Jeff Beck with three awards each.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] The Black Keys, Eminem, Herbie Hancock, Alicia Keys, The Roots, Usher, Christopher Tin and BeBe Winans won two awards each.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] The television broadcast of the 53rd Grammy Awards marked the last awards show for the Grammy's executive producer, John Cossette, before his death on April 26, 2011.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] At the request of manager and music impresario, Lisa Roy, the album was compiled and mastered by music producer, Stewart Cararas.
[src:afrojack/53rd-annual-grammy-awards] All attendees of the 2011 Academy Awards received the CD in their gift bags.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] The **54th Annual Grammy Awards** were held on February 12, 2012, at the Staples Center in Los Angeles being broadcast on CBS honoring the best in music for the recording year beginning October 1, 2010 through September 30, 2011.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] It was the first time in seven years that the event had an official host.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] Nominations were announced on November 30, 2011, on prime-time television as part of "The GRAMMY Nominations Concert Live! – Countdown to Music's Biggest Night", a one-hour special broadcast live on CBS from Nokia Theatre at L.A.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] Kanye West received the most nominations with seven.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] Adele, Foo Fighters, and Bruno Mars each received six nominations.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] Lil Wayne, Skrillex, and Radiohead all earned five nominations.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] The nominations were criticised by many music journalists as Kanye West's *My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy* missed out on a nomination for Album of the Year despite being highly critically acclaimed and topping many end of year charts.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] West's album went on to win Best Rap Album.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] A total of 78 awards were presented following the academy's decision to restructure the Grammy Award categories.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] Paul McCartney received the MusiCares Person of the Year award on February 10, 2012, at the Los Angeles Convention Center, two nights prior to the Grammy telecast.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] On February 8, 2012, the academy announced that the 54th Grammy Pre-Telecast Ceremony would stream live internationally.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] The ceremony took place at the Los Angeles Convention Center and was streamed live in its entirety internationally at Grammy's official website and CBS Television Network.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] The ceremony was co-hosted by Dave Koz and MC Lyte.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] A total of 68 awards were presented in the Pre-Telecast ceremony.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] The official poster was designed by architect Frank Gehry.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] On February 7, 2012, following Etta James' death on January 20, 2012, The Recording Academy announced a tribute performance Alicia Keys and Bonnie Raitt.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] The day before the ceremony, Whitney Houston died in Los Angeles, and the show's producers quickly planned a tribute in the form of Jennifer Hudson singing Houston's "I Will Always Love You".
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] The awards show began with a Bruce Springsteen performance followed by an LL Cool J prayer for Whitney Houston.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] Adele won all of her six nominations, equalling the record for most wins by a female artist in one night, first held by Beyoncé.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] Adele became only the second artist in history, following Christopher Cross in 1981, to have won all four of the general field (Album of the Year, Best New Artist, Record of the Year and Song of the Year) awards throughout her career.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] Foo Fighters and Kanye West followed with five and four awards, respectively.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] With his win for Best Musical Theater Album (for *The Book of Mormon: Original Broadway Cast Recording*), producer Scott Rudin became the 11th person to become an EGOT winner.
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] The anticipation for the show's tributes to Whitney Houston greatly helped increase the ratings for the 54th Grammy Awards, which became the second highest in its history with 39.9 million viewers (trailing only behind the 1984 Grammys with 51.67 million viewers).
[src:afrojack/54th-annual-grammy-awards] This remains the highest-rated Grammy telecast on 21st-century U.S. television.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The **64th Annual Grammy Awards** ceremony was held at the MGM Grand Garden Arena in Las Vegas on April 3, 2022.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] It recognized the best recordings, compositions, and artists of the eligibility year, running from September 1, 2020, to September 30, 2021.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The nominations were revealed via a virtual livestream on November 23, 2021.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The performers for the ceremony were announced on March 15, 24, and 30, 2022.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] South African comedian Trevor Noah, who hosted the previous ceremony in 2021, returned as host.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The ceremony's location marked the first time the Recording Academy switched host cities for a single ceremony.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] This also makes it the first Grammy Awards ceremony not to be held in either New York City or Los Angeles since the 15th Grammy Awards in 1973 when it was held at the Tennessee Theatre in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] It marked the first time the telecast took place in Las Vegas.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] Jon Batiste received the most nominations with eleven, followed by Doja Cat, H.E.R., and Justin Bieber with eight each.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] Batiste received the most awards with five, and won Album of the Year for *We Are*.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] Silk Sonic won Record of the Year and Song of the Year for "Leave the Door Open", and Olivia Rodrigo won Best New Artist.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The ceremony was originally scheduled for January 31, 2022, at the Crypto.com Arena in Los Angeles; however, on January 5, 2022, the Recording Academy postponed the ceremony indefinitely due to health and safety concerns related to the COVID-19 Omicron variant.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] On January 18, 2022, the ceremony was rescheduled to April 3, 2022, and its location was moved to the MGM Grand Garden Arena in Las Vegas, due to resultant scheduling conflicts with the Crypto.com Arena.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The academy announced Trevor Noah to return as the host of the ceremony.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] For the 2022 ceremony, the Recording Academy opted to eliminate its nomination review committees, which were previously responsible for determining the nominees of each category.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] Nominees would be solely decided based on votes from the Recording Academy.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] For the 2022 ceremony and during both voting rounds, the number of categories members of the Recording Academy were allowed to vote in was reduced to ten, on top of the four major categories.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The ten categories could belong to up to three different fields, including the genre fields.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The changes were made to "help ensure the quality of voting".
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] Drake was initially announced as a nominee for Best Rap Performance (for "Way 2 Sexy") and Best Rap Album (for *Certified Lover Boy*), but withdrew from contention for both awards on December 6, 2021.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The Recording Academy subsequently honored Drake's request and officially removed his nominations for both awards.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The ceremony was originally scheduled to be held on January 31, 2022, at the Crypto.com Arena in Los Angeles.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] On January 5, 2022, the Recording Academy postponed the ceremony indefinitely due to health and safety concerns related to the COVID-19 Omicron variant.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] With the Crypto.com Arena booked with sports games and concerts nearly every night through mid-April, the academy decided to switch the ceremony's location to the MGM Grand Garden Arena in Las Vegas.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The MGM Grand Garden Arena hosted the Latin Grammy Awards for six years, including the 22nd Annual Latin Grammy Awards in November 2021.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The performers for the ceremony were announced on March 25, 2022.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] Foo Fighters were announced as a performer on March 24, one day before the death of their drummer Taylor Hawkins.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The band canceled their performance at the ceremony on March 31.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] A tribute montage dedicated to Hawkins and set to "My Hero" was aired during the ceremony before the in memoriam segment.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The Recording Academy banned Kanye West—who was nominated for five awards—from performing, citing his "concerning online behavior".
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] NPR and *Variety* tied the decision to West's outbursts regarding his divorce from Kim Kardashian, his harassment of Kardashian's then-boyfriend Pete Davidson, and an Instagram post in which he insulted Noah using a racial slur.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p01] The decision was criticized by Noah, who said he did not want to "cancel" West, and the Game, who argued it was disrespectful to hip-hop.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p02] Winners appear first and highlighted in **bold**.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p03] A tribute to victims of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine was featured with a performance of "Go Down Moses".
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p03] Prior to the performance, a short video of Volodymyr Zelenskyy concerning the circumstances of warfare and military activity in Ukraine was played.
[src:afrojack/64th-annual-grammy-awards-p03] Zelenskyy's appearance was seen by some as a way to make up for the rejection of the similar idea during the 94th Academy Awards the week before.
[src:afrojack/a-msterdamn] "**A Msterdamn**" is a song by Dutch music producer and DJ Afrojack in collaboration with Dutch DJ-team the Partysquad.
[src:afrojack/a-msterdamn] The single was released digitally on 10 May 2010 in the Netherlands.
[src:afrojack/a-msterdamn] The music video was released on 27 March 2010 on the official Spinnin' Records YouTube channel.
[src:afrojack/a-msterdamn] It shows two people having an evening of alcohol, illegal parties, strip clubs, marijuana and cocaine until, they are beaten by a lady.
[src:afrojack/a-msterdamn] Then at the end, the two people were with prostitutes.
[src:afrojack/afrojack-discography] This is the discography of Dutch DJ and record producer Afrojack.
[src:afrojack/afrojack-discography] His song "Take Over Control", which features Dutch singer Eva Simons, charted in 10 different countries.
[src:afrojack/afrojack-discography] He released his debut EP *Lost & Found* on December 22, 2010.
[src:afrojack/afrojack-discography] In 2011, he was featured on Pitbull's number 1 hit single "Give Me Everything" along with Ne-Yo and Nayer.
[src:afrojack/afrojack-discography] He also contributed to the single "Run the World (Girls)" by Beyoncé, who initially did not include his credits on the track but was eventually forced to do so after Afrojack filed a case against her.
[src:afrojack/afrojack-discography] His debut album, *Forget the World*, was released on 16 May 2014.
[src:afrojack/afrojack-discography] "—" denotes a recording that did not chart or was not released in that territory.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] Nick Leonardus Van de Wall was born in Spijkenisse, South Holland, to a Dutch mother and a Surinamese father.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] He developed an interest in music at an early age and learned to play the piano at the age of five.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] From a single-parent household, his mother Debbie owned a local gym.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] After leaving school, Van de Wall studied graphic design at the Grafisch Lyceum in Rotterdam for a year before embarking on a career as a DJ/producer.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] At the age of 14, Van de Wall started DJing at local pubs and clubs and earning additional income by designing websites for fellow musicians.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In 2007, he released "In Your Face", the first recording under the Afrojack name.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] He received international success with the song "Take Over Control" featuring Eva Simons, which charted in 10 countries.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] He took part in Episode 2 of 'Behind The Speedo', which is a comedy series by Redfoo.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] His 2010 entry into the poll at number 19 was the highest new entry of that year's list.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] Afrojack was listed as number 7 on the *DJ Mag* Top 100 DJs of 2011.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] He ranked at number 9 on *DJ Mag's* Top 100 DJs of 2012.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In July 2010, Afrojack created an Essential Mix for BBC Radio 1.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] He released the *Lost & Found* EP on 22 December 2010.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] He also contributed to the single "Run the World (Girls)" by Beyoncé.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In January 2012 Afrojack received a European Border Breakers Award.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] Afrojack's newest single "The Spark" featuring Spree Wilson hit number 3 in Australia and New Zealand, and top 10 in over 7 more countries.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In 2013, Afrojack was the 7th highest-earning DJ in the world, according to *Forbes* magazine.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In 2011, Afrojack co-produced music with many artists including David Guetta, Mike Brown and Madonna.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In 2012, he was a headliner at a number of electronic dance music festivals, including Tomorrowland, Ultra Music Festival, and Coachella.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] His debut album, *Forget the World*, was released on 19 May 2014 to mixed reviews.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] On 17 March 2015, Afrojack was featured in David Guetta's single "Hey Mama" in which he co-produced with Guetta.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] The song featured him along with Nicki Minaj and Bebe Rexha.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] On 27 July 2017, he released the *NLW EP* under the alias NLW.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] This marked the launch of his new alias NLW under which he would go on to produce more underground style tracks.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In 2016, one of his songs, "Braver", was featured on the game *Final Fantasy XV*.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] He appeared in the 2016 documentary film about American DJ and producer Steve Aoki, titled *I'll Sleep When I'm Dead*, which was subsequently nominated for a Grammy Award.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] On 28 April 2017, he released a new single "Another Life" collaborating with fellow DJ David Guetta featuring Ester Dean.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] On 7 September 2017, he released the single "No Tomorrow" featuring Belly, O.T.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] On 14 February 2018, he released his track "Bed of Roses" featuring Stanaj, which was played as an ID during his set at Ultra Music Festival 2017 in Miami.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In July 2018, at Tomorrowland in Boom, Belgium, he debuted many of his new tracks such as "Bassride", "Step Back", which are all included in his *Press Play* EP, releasing on 31 August 2018.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In March 2020, Afrojack announced that he would perform at the Eurovision Song Contest 2020, in Rotterdam alongside Glennis Grace, however, the contest was cancelled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] He performed at the contest the following year, in the same city.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In March 2022, Afrojack released a new track along with David Guetta called "Trampoline." The song also features Missy Elliott, Bia and Doechii.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In September 2022, Afrojack announced "Jack to the Future" US tour.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] Since 2007, Afrojack runs his own label, Wall Recordings, which represents producers including KIIDA, Apster, D-Wayne, D.O.D, Karim Mika, and others.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] The label used to operate as a sub-label to Spinnin' Records until late January 2016.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] Tom & Jame's Burn Down marked the last release of Wall Recordings as a sub-label.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] After going independent for a while, it became a sub-label to Armada Music in 2017, until it became independent again in 2019.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] In 2019, Afrojack and Italian heiress, singer, socialite Elettra Lamborghini made their engagement public.
[src:afrojack/afrojack] The two were married on 26 September 2020 at Lake Como, Italy.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] After graduating junior high school, Shiono helped his parents' restaurant instead of going to high school.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] While recommended from the store customers and his mother, he was a candidate in the 24th *Junon Super Boy contest*, which was held in 2011, he was awarded the Special Jury Prize and the Prize Aoki.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] In March 2012, Shiono became affiliated with Oscar Promotion.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] In 2013, he appeared in *Zyuden Sentai Kyoryuger* as Souji Rippukan/Kyoryu Green.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] In the film *Zyuden Sentai Kyoryuger Returns: Hundred Years After*, he played Soujiro.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] In 2016, Shiono performed the starring role of Masamune Date in Sengoku Basara 4 Sumeragi play.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] In November 2017, Shiono became vice leader of Aoyama Omotesando X Male Troupe.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] On 6 April 2019, Shiono played Kansuke Yamamoto role in Shingen-ko festival.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] Kansuke Yamamoto was known as a brilliant strategist and particularly known for his plan which led to victory in the fourth battle of Kawanakajima.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] Shingen-ko is the Guinness-registered Largest Samurai Festival in all over the world.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] Also, Shiono met Nagasaki Prefectural Governor to discuss about this important traditional festival on 5 April.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] On 28 February 2021, Shiono left Oscar Promotion and Aoyama Omotesando X.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] On 12 August 2021, Shiono joined LDH Japan.
[src:afrojack/akihisa-shiono] Shiono's hobbies are playing tennis and he is good at cooking crêpe.
[src:afrojack/albert-stanaj] Stanaj was born to an Albanian family on 12 February 1994 in Shkodër, Albania and was raised in the city of New York, the United States.
[src:afrojack/albert-stanaj] He attended the Archbishop Stepinac High School in White Plains, New York.
[src:afrojack/albert-stanaj] He also participated in numerous music festivals in Albania, Europe as well as the United States.
[src:afrojack/albert-stanaj] At 18, he moved to Los Angeles to continue his professional musical career.
[src:afrojack/albert-stanaj] His debut single "Ain't Love Strange" released in 2016 peaked at number two in Albania.
[src:afrojack/albert-stanaj] Stanaj has cited Justin Timberlake, Maxwell, Michael Jackson and Whitney Houston as his major influences.
